South African Stocks Climb to Six-Week High; Metorex Jumps, Nedbank Gains

-- B y   S i k o n a t h i   M a n t s h a n t s h a
-- 
2011-04-04T17:07:02Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-04/south-african-equities-rise-for-2nd-day-anglo-bhp-metorex-nedbank-move.html
(Corrects to show Nedbank share price fell.)  South Africa ’s FTSE/JSE Africa All
Share Index rose to the highest level in six weeks, adding
52.45, or 0.2 percent, to 32,437.77 at the 5 p.m. close in
Johannesburg.  The following were among the most active stocks in the
South African market today.  Anglo American Plc (AGL)  , the diversified mining company
that makes up 11 percent of South Africa’s benchmark stock
index, snapped two days of losses, gaining 4.80 rand, or 1.4
percent, to 356 rand. Copper rose in  New York  after  China ’s
Minmetals Resources Ltd. offered about $6.5 billion for copper
miner Equinox Minerals Ltd., reviving speculation of more demand
for the metal by China, the world’s largest buyer.  BHP Billiton
Plc (BIL)  , the world’s largest mining company, increased for
a fifth day, advancing 3.50 rand, or 1.3 percent, to 273.90
rand.  Metorex Ltd. (MTX)  , a coal and base metal miner, jumped
to the highest level since October 2008, adding 35 cents, or 5.4
percent, to 6.80 rand. The company said its copper-mineral
reserves increased by 3 percent and that its cobalt reserves
rose 49 percent.  Nedbank Group Ltd. (NED)  , the South African bank
controlled by  Old Mutual Plc (OML)  , fell 1.04 rand, or 0.7
percent, to 141.96 rand. Standard Chartered Plc may bid for Old
Mutual’s 52 percent stake in the bank, according to a report in
South Africa’s  Sunday Times  newspaper. The paper did not say
where it got the information. Separately, Standard Chartered’s
Islamic unit, the Dubai-based Standard Chartered Saadiq, said it
is “exploring opportunities” for expansion into Nigeria,
Tanzania and  Kenya , according to Chief Executive Officer Afaq Khan.  To contact the reporter on this story:
